PARAGRAPH.#text: By Marietta Cauchi Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES LONDON (Dow Jones)--Several buyout firms submitted second round bids for Astra Tech, the dental and healthcare unit being sold by AstraZeneca PLC (AZN.LN), by Monday's deadline, people familiar with the situation told Dow Jones Newswires Tuesday. Bridgepoint, Cinven and PAI Partners put in bids for the healthcare part of the business while EQT is trying to buy the whole unit, they added. It is unclear whether Warburg Pincus, an early bidder, remains interested and, if so, how much of the business it has bid for.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Buyout Firms Submit Second Round Bids For Astra Tech - Sources

Headlines.SeoHeadline: HEARD ON THE STREET: No School Spirit
Headlines.Headline: No School Spirit

PARAGRAPH.#text: It isn't just investors being taught a lesson by the slump in education stocks. After Strayer Education reported a 20% fall in winter-term new student enrollment, one analyst lamented it isn't just the sector with an overcapacity problem. With declining deal flow and trading revenue, the sector looks over-covered by Wall Street. Some 22 analysts cover industry bellwether Apollo Group. Yet FactSet data show the leading firm in the similarly sized health-care-supplies sector, Dentsply International, is covered by just 10. Going public is no picnic. Just four U.S. retail companies had initial public offerings in 2010, accounting for 2% of the $35.7 billion in total volume, says Dealogic. So it's little surprise Crumbs Holdings is trying the backdoor. The fast-growing cupcake retailer said Monday it plans to sell itself to a special-purpose acquisition company that will rename itself Crumbs Bake Shop and trade on Nasdaq. After Krispy Kreme's spectacular rise and fall, investors should beware gorging on cupcakes.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: No School Spirit
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Goran Mijuk
Headlines.Headline: Dental Implant Sector Set For Demand Surge, More M&A In 2011

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Goran Mijuk Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES ZURICH (Dow Jones)--Executives of large dental implant makers say their business will take a bigger bite of overall consumer spending next year, despite continued weakness in the global economy and stiff price competition from new entrants. Expansion rates of 5% are realistic for 2011, they say, while double-digit growth is possible in two years once consumers regain confidence, reversing a more than 6% drop that hurt the $18 billion dental industry in the downturn.

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Dentsply International Inc.'s XRAY third-quarter profit fell 5.7% amid lower margins and higher overhead costs. The dental-products maker also lowered the top end of its 2010 earnings view. Last month, Standard & Poor's Ratings Services lifted its rating on Dentsply, saying the dental-products maker's operating performance has been resilient in the face of the weak global economy. For the latest quarter, Dentsply posted a profit of $63.7 million, or 44 cents a share, down from $67.5 million, or 45 cents a share, a year earlier.

Headlines.Headline: Straumann's Quarterly Sales Hit By Strong Swiss Franc

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds CEO, analyst comment.) ZURICH (Dow Jones)--Dental implant maker Straumann Holding AG (STMN.EB) Thursday reported a 3.9% drop in third-quarter sales as the strong Swiss franc shaved its top line, but said it still expects to grow above the market in 2010 although it warned that volatile currency moves could undermine its targets. The Switzerland-based company said sales in the three months to the end of September rose to 161.6 million Swiss francs, or about $163.5 million, from CHF168.2 million a year earlier, failing to meet analyst forecasts of CHF165 million as the Swiss franc and continually weak markets in Europe undermined strong growth in emerging markets such as Latin America and a nascent recovery in U.S.
